
# Supporting Notes - AI-Powered SEO Content Production Research

## Research Goal

My goal with this project is not only to collect expert content, but to build a source base strong enough to support a real playbook later for **AI-powered SEO content production**.

I wanted to study practitioners whose work could help answer questions like:

- how AI visibility differs from traditional rankings
- what kinds of content systems still matter in AI-search environments
- how brand, entities, citations, and cross-format content influence discoverability
- what practical workflows might actually work for B2B SaaS or similar contexts

## How I Chose My Sources

I did not want to rely on the first generic names that appeared in Google results.

Instead, I used:

- the Wellows article on top AI SEO agencies
- LinkedIn recommendations
- my discussion with Claude about strong SEO and AI practitioners
- extra research into expert backgrounds, their companies, and the kinds of content they publish

From that wider pool, I selected the experts whose material felt:

- more niche and interesting
- more practical than generic
- more likely to help me build a real framework or playbook later

## Why The Material Feels Strong Enough For A Future Playbook

This research set feels useful because it gives me a mix of:

- recent LinkedIn posts for fresh observations and framing
- YouTube interviews and talks for longer explanations
- transcript files for raw source material
- my own notes for what stood out and why it matters

That gives me a better foundation for later synthesis instead of only collecting links.

## Technical Workflow I Used

This project also required me to use more technical tools than I expected at first.

I used:

- `Cursor IDE` as my main working environment
- `Git` and `GitHub` for version control
- `Git Bash` as one of the terminals I used during setup and repository work
- `Python` for transcript collection
- `youtube-transcript-api` to pull YouTube transcripts
- `Node.js` for additional environment setup

I also worked with a custom AI setup:

- I used my own `SumoPod` API key
- because that workflow was more manual, I installed `WSL`
- I used the `WSL` terminal inside Cursor IDE
- I configured SumoPod manually there
- I installed Claude Code manually through the terminal
- I configured the model manually as `Sonnet 4.6`

I also used `Codex` for many of the fixes when I still had unresolved terminal issues. That was especially helpful when I got stuck on setup problems, file structure issues, transcript collection workflow, and Git-related confusion.

## What I Have Organized So Far

- `research/sources.md` contains the ranked source list and why the chosen experts matter
- `research/linkedin-posts/` contains recent LinkedIn research notes
- `research/youtube-transcripts/` contains transcript-first files organized by video
- transcript files also include my own notes at the end so the raw material and my takeaways stay connected

## Workflow Note

I committed and pushed my work regularly instead of waiting until the very end. That helped me keep the repo organized while I was still learning, troubleshooting, and improving the research structure.
